<p class="p2"><span class="s1">The third week of my REU is coming to a close.  Here's what I've worked on so far.</b>
<p>
A sequence \(z_n \in \mathbb{D}\) is called "interpolating" if for every other sequence \(x_n \in \ell^{\infty}(\mathbb{D})\), there is some bounded analytic function \(f \in H^{\infty}(\mathbb{D}\)
for which \(f(z_n) = a_n\) for all \(n\).  This seems like a pretty strict condition, but Carleson (see, e.g., Garnett, "Bounded Analytic Functions") showed that the following are equivalent: <ul>
<li>A sequence is interpolating</li>
<li>\[\inf_n \prod_{m\neq n}\rho(z_n, z_m) > 0\]</li>
<li>\(\inf_{n, m} \rho(a_n, a_m) > 0\), and furthermore, </li>
</ul>
where \(\rho\) is the pseudohyperbolic metric \(\rho(z, w) \coloneq \left|\frac{z-w}{z\overline{w} - 1}\right|\).  If you are familiar with the Blaschke map, you'll see this is the same thing.
</p>

